"""
mkt-context | judges | ch9–10 fill
present: ch9:v1,4,7,23,53; ch10:v6,11,14,16 — 66 missing
run: python3 scripts/zc-context-judges-9-10-fill.py

Ch9: Abimelech's kingship experiment — political/ANE context, fable genre, Shechem archaeology
Ch10: Minor judges, double Philistine-Ammonite oppression, covenant lawsuit form
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{layer}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JUDGES = {
  "9": {
    "2": "<p>Abimelech's appeal to the Shechemites — 'Remember that I am your bone and flesh' — exploits his dual lineage: he is Gideon's son but his mother was a Shechemite concubine. The kinship-appeal (<em>ʿeṣem ûbāśār</em>, bone and flesh) is the standard ANE covenant-bond formula, signaling that Abimelech presents himself not as an outsider claiming kingship but as a local son with legitimate ties. That he appeals to Shechemite kinship rather than Israelite covenant identity exposes his political base as ethnic rather than covenantal — he is building a city-state monarchy on Canaanite rather than Yahwistic foundations.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Abimelech's maternal uncles repeat his appeal to all the lords of Shechem — the <em>ba'alê šĕkem</em> (lords/masters of Shechem) are the city's ruling oligarchy. Ancient Shechem (Tell Balata) was a major Canaanite city-state with a long history of treaty relationships with surrounding peoples. The Amarna letters (14th century BCE) document Shechem's king Labaya as a habiru-allied troublemaker who played Egyptian power against local city-states — exactly the kind of political maneuvering that Abimelech's story replays on a smaller scale. The transfer of civic loyalty from a potential tribal confederation to one oligarchically-approved man is the first step of the tyranny the fable will diagnose.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'He went to his father's house at Ophrah and killed his brothers the sons of Jerubbaal, seventy men, on one stone.' The mass execution 'on one stone' (<em>ʿal-ʾeben ʾaḥat</em>) is a deliberate royal action — not a battlefield killing but a formal execution site. Ancient Near Eastern kings executed rivals by public decapitation, typically of claimants to the throne; 70 brothers represents the virtual elimination of the entire Gideon lineage. The single stone serving as an execution platform is a specific detail that functions as a judicial altar-perversion: the stone on which God's people offer sacrifices is turned into a place of dynastic bloodshed. Only Jotham, the youngest, escapes by hiding.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'And all the leaders of Shechem and all Beth-millo came together, and they went and made Abimelech king, by the oak of the pillar at Shechem.' Beth-millo (literally 'house of the filling/rampart') is likely the citadel quarter of Shechem, the fortified upper city section. The oak/terebinth at Shechem had deep covenantal associations: Joshua had set up a large stone under an oak at Shechem as a covenant memorial (Josh 24:26); the oak of Moreh near Shechem was where YHWH appeared to Abraham (Gen 12:6). Making Abimelech king at this sacred site was a deliberate appropriation of Israel's covenant-renewal location for a Canaanite-style kingship installation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The fable's opening — 'The trees once went to anoint a king over them' (<em>hālōk hālĕkû hāʿēṣîm limšōaḥ ʿălêhem melek</em>) — uses the Infinitive Absolute construction to emphasize the earnestness of the trees' search. The anointing (<em>māšaḥ</em>) of the trees' king deliberately inverts the legitimate anointing of Israel's leaders by YHWH's chosen servants (Samuel anointing Saul, David). The fable's satirical edge is that the trees — representing the capable leaders of Israel — serially refuse leadership; only the useless bramble accepts it, and its acceptance is a threat disguised as an offer.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The olive tree's refusal — 'Should I stop producing my oil by which gods and men are honored, and go to sway over the trees?' — encodes a genuine insight about the cost of political leadership. The olive oil was used for the Tabernacle lamp (Exod 27:20), for anointing (Exod 30:24), and as the primary cooking fat and skin-care product of the ancient world — it was the most economically and liturgically valuable agricultural product in Canaan. A leader who abandons productive stewardship to acquire positional power is giving up genuine substance for nominal rule — the fable's warning about what true leadership costs.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The fig tree is the second to refuse: 'Should I stop producing my sweetness and my good fruit and go to sway over the trees?' The fig was, with the olive and grape, one of the three primary crops of Canaan (Deut 8:8); its sweetness made it a luxury food and trade item. The parallelism between the olive's 'oil/fatness,' the fig's 'sweetness/good fruit,' and the vine's 'wine that cheers' (v13) creates a graduated list of Israel's covenant blessings — each of which is threatened by the wrong kind of leadership. The fable argues that good leadership serves the fruit-bearing of the community; bad leadership (the bramble) destroys it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The fig tree's refusal focuses on concrete productivity over symbolic authority — 'my sweetness and my good fruit' vs. 'swaying over the trees.' The verb <em>nûaʿ</em> (to sway, move) used for what the appointed king would do over the trees is usually translated 'hold sway' but can also mean 'to shake/totter' — an ironic image of royal instability. The fable thus embeds in its grammar the instability that Abimelech's reign will demonstrate: he who sways over others is himself unsteady, unlike the fruitful fig or olive which are rooted and producing.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The vine is the third candidate asked to be king. In ANE royal iconography, the vine was associated with royal gardens and prosperity; the Ugaritic texts describe El's divine garden as a vineyard. That the vine also refuses to exchange fruitfulness for sway over others follows the fable's consistent logic. The progression olive → fig → vine represents the full sweep of Israel's agricultural economy; that all three refuse leadership suggests not laziness but a proper ordering of priorities — contributing to others' flourishing rather than ruling over them.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Should I stop producing my wine that cheers God and men, and go to sway over the trees?' The wine that 'cheers God and men' (<em>tiśmaḥ ʾĕlōhîm wăʾănāšîm</em>) refers to the libation offerings of wine poured before YHWH (Num 15:5-10; Exod 29:40) and to the human joy that wine creates. The vine's twin service — to the divine cult and to human pleasure — captures the dual obligation of Israel's covenant life: worshipping YHWH and cultivating human flourishing. Both are abandoned when the vine takes up the politically-motivated 'swaying' role the fable critiques.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Then all the trees said to the bramble, You come and reign over us.' The bramble (<em>ʾāṭād</em>) — a thorny shrub of no agricultural value, useless for fruit, timber, or shade — is what the trees finally get when all productive options have refused. The bramble is a species of Ziziphus or Rhamnus, a thorny scrub plant common in rocky Israelite terrain. The irony is multivalent: the bramble produces nothing useful, its only notable property is its thorns (which cause pain), and its offer of 'shade' (v15) is physically absurd — a bramble provides no shade. Abimelech is the human bramble: his only qualification is that he wanted power when worthier men declined it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'If in good faith you are anointing me king over you, then come and take refuge in my shadow, but if not, let fire come out of the bramble and devour the cedars of Lebanon.' The bramble's conditional offer exposes the tyrannical logic of illegitimate power: it demands complete submission ('take refuge in my shadow') or threatens total destruction ('fire from the bramble'). The threat is disproportionate — a bramble threatening to devour Lebanon's cedars — satirizing the megalomania of petty tyrants. Bramble fires were historically destructive in dry seasons (cf. Exod 22:6 on fire in thorns spreading to fields); the image of the smallest, most worthless plant threatening the greatest and most valuable trees is Jotham's thesis about Abimelech in a nutshell.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jotham's application of the fable (vv16-20) is a formal covenant address: 'If then you acted in good faith and integrity when you made Abimelech king...' The condition <em>be'emet ûvĕtāmîm</em> (in truth and integrity) is the covenant standard language (cf. Josh 24:14: 'serve him in sincerity and faithfulness'). Jotham applies the fable by asking whether Shechem's action met the covenant standard — which it manifestly did not, given the seventy murders on one stone. The fable provides the diagnostic framework; the application delivers the verdict.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'For my father fought for you and risked his life and delivered you from the hand of Midian.' The reminder of Gideon's service to Shechem is the prosecution's evidence: those who were saved by Jerubbaal's self-risk are now slaughtering his sons. The phrase 'he cast his life before him' (<em>wayyašlēk ʾet-napšô minnegdô</em>) — risked his life, literally 'cast his life in front of himself' — is an idiom for reckless bravery in service of others. The contrast between Gideon's self-giving and Abimelech's self-aggrandizement is the moral fulcrum of the entire chapter.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And you have risen against my father's house this day and have killed his sons, seventy men on one stone, and have made Abimelech, the son of his female servant, king over the leaders of Shechem, because he is your brother.' The social status of Abimelech's mother — a concubine/female servant (<em>ʾāmāh</em>) — is deployed here as evidence of the absurdity of the choice: Shechem has rejected 70 legitimate sons to install a concubine's son. The ancient Near East had strict hierarchies of wife-status and son-legitimacy; a concubine's son was generally ineligible for primary inheritance (cf. Ishmael, Jephthah). Abimelech's low-status origin makes his royal ambition doubly illegitimate.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'If you then have acted in good faith and integrity with Jerubbaal and with his house this day, then rejoice in Abimelech, and let him also rejoice in you.' The conditional structure of the covenant loyalty-assessment reaches its logical conclusion: if the action was legitimate, celebrate it; if not (which the argument has shown), accept the consequences. The covenant form demands that Israel evaluate its actions not by their outcomes but by their correspondence with the standard of <em>emet vetamim</em> (truth and integrity). Shechem's action failed that test, and the fable's curse will follow.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'But if not, let fire come out from Abimelech and devour the leaders of Shechem and Beth-millo; and let fire come out from the leaders of Shechem and from Beth-millo and devour Abimelech.' The mutual-destruction curse is the culmination of Jotham's covenant address, applying the fable's bramble-fire directly to the Abimelech-Shechem relationship. The form is reciprocal — each will destroy the other — which is precisely what happens in vv41-49 (Abimelech destroys Shechem) and v54 (Abimelech himself dies). Jotham's curse is the formal invocation of the covenant curse mechanism: YHWH enforces covenant violation through the destruction of the parties themselves.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Then Jotham ran away and fled and went to Beer and lived there, because of Abimelech his brother.' Beer's location is unknown; Jotham goes into exile to escape his brother's reach. His exile is a structural parallel to Cain's exile (Gen 4:16) and Abimelek's own use of sanctuary-flight (Abimelech = father of height/king; his name's meaning ironizes his kingship throughout). The flight of the truth-teller before the tyrant is a recurring biblical pattern: prophets flee kings (Elijah from Jezebel, 1 Kings 19:3); wisdom speaks from the margins when power becomes corrupted. Jotham's fable and flight will be vindicated three years later.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Abimelech's three-year reign is explicitly not called a judgeship — the text uses <em>wayyāśar</em> (he ruled/governed) rather than the standard judge vocabulary. Three years is the shortest tenure in Judges, appropriate to the illegitimate nature of the rule. The contrast with the genuine judges' periods of rest (40 years for Othniel and Barak; 80 for Ehud) underscores the transience of self-appointed power versus YHWH-appointed deliverers. Abimelech governs; he does not judge or save — the distinction between coercive power and covenantal leadership is embedded in the narrative's vocabulary.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The divine purpose behind the Abimelech-Shechem conflict is stated: 'that the violence done to the seventy sons of Jerubbaal might come, and their blood be laid on Abimelech their brother, who killed them, and on the men of Shechem, who strengthened his hands to kill his brothers.' YHWH engineers retribution through human conflict — the same mechanism described in v23 ('God sent an evil spirit'). This is the Deuteronomistic principle that covenant violation carries within itself the seeds of self-destruction: the crime and the punishment are structurally connected, not externally imposed.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Shechemite ambushes against Abimelech begin the civil dissolution of the coup. Setting ambushes on the mountain roads was a standard bandit/insurgency tactic in antiquity; the mountain passes around Shechem controlled trade routes between the coastal plain and the Jordan valley. The shift from Shechem supporting Abimelech to Shechem ambushing travelers represents the fractured loyalty that the evil spirit (v23) produced — the city's oligarchy turns against its own creation when the honeymoon of the kingship experiment ends.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Gaal son of Ebed arrives at Shechem — his name may mean 'loathing, disgust' (perhaps a pejorative epithet), and <em>Ebed</em> means 'servant.' His appearance introduces a rival claimant who exploits Shechem's disillusionment with Abimelech. The vintage festival context (vv26-27) is significant: wine harvest celebrations were times of communal gathering, heightened emotion, and political speeches — in antiquity, the feast was the natural forum for political agitation. Gaal leads the city's rebellion from within the festival context, where Shechemite identity and communal solidarity were at their peak.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Shechemites celebrate their vintage and 'went into the house of their god and ate and drank and reviled Abimelech.' The temple feast and the political conspiracy are simultaneous — the Baal-Berith temple (whose treasury had funded Abimelech's coup in v4) now becomes the venue of his denunciation. The political and religious were not separable in the ancient city-state: the city-god's feast was the political assembly. Gaal's rebellion is simultaneously a religious and a political challenge to Abimelech — which is why Abimelech's response (burning the El-Berith temple with its occupants, v46-49) is so total.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Gaal's taunt — 'Who is Abimelech, and who is Shechem, that we should serve him? Is he not the son of Jerubbaal, and is not Zebul his officer?' — appeals to Shechemite ethnic pride over their Israelite-connected king. The reference to the 'men of Hamor the father of Shechem' invokes the pre-Israelite Hivite founders of Shechem (Gen 34:2), asserting authentic local identity against an interloper. This ethnic appeal to pre-Israelite Shechemite identity demonstrates the continuing Canaanite cultural undercurrent within the city that the conquest had never fully displaced.</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Would that this people were under my hand! Then I would remove Abimelech. I would say to Abimelech, Increase your army and come out.' Gaal's hypothetical challenge is the reckless boasting of a political opportunist — he claims he would challenge Abimelech if only he had power, which he does not yet have. The pattern of the taunt-before-battle that leads to humiliating defeat is a recurring biblical motif (cf. Goliath's taunt in 1 Sam 17; Sennacherib's boasting in 2 Kings 18-19). Gaal's words at the feast will prove empty when Abimelech actually appears the next morning.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Zebul, the city ruler of Shechem and Abimelech's deputy, hears Gaal's words and sends word to Abimelech in anger. Zebul's loyalty to Abimelech despite the city's rebellion represents the faction of the Shechemite oligarchy that had committed to the new political order and could not afford to reverse it. The intelligence network implied — a city ruler spying on public speeches at a temple feast and sending night messages to the king — reflects the kind of covert political surveillance that characterized ancient Near Eastern monarchies. Abimelech governs through informants as well as force.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'They are stirring up the city against you.' The verb <em>ṣwr</em> (to besiege/incite) in its Piel form means to stir up, incite to rebellion — Gaal is not merely speaking but actively organizing the city against Abimelech. The political situation Zebul describes is the urban insurrection pattern: an outside agitator arrives, exploits existing resentment, organizes within the city's political/religious institutions (the temple feast), and challenges the established power. Abimelech's response (vv32-33) is a classic counter-insurgency operation: night movement, ambush positions, morning attack before the rebels can organize.</p>",
    "32": "<p>'Now therefore, go by night, you and the people who are with you, and set an ambush in the field.' The tactical instruction Zebul gives Abimelech is a night flanking maneuver — move to ambush positions while darkness provides cover, then engage the rebels when they sortie from the city at dawn. This mirrors the Gideon operation of ch7 (night approach, dawn attack) and the general pattern of Israelite guerrilla warfare against stronger fortified opponents. Abimelech's military competence — whatever his political illegitimacy — is consistently on display throughout ch9.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'Then in the morning, as soon as the sun is up, rise early and rush upon the city. And when he and the people who are with him come out against you, you may do to them as your hand finds.' The phrase 'as your hand finds' (<em>kaʾašer timṣā yādĕkā</em>) is a legal-military idiom giving Abimelech discretionary authority over prisoners and combatants — the equivalent of modern rules of engagement with wide latitude. Zebul's instructions give Abimelech both the tactical advantage (surprise, flanking, timing) and the legal authorization for whatever violence is necessary. The combination of intelligence, strategy, and authorization is the counter-insurgency toolkit of the ancient period.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Abimelech's force divides into four companies — a tactically sophisticated division that could cover multiple approach routes and prevent escape. The four-company envelopment recurs in Saul's battles (1 Sam 11:11; 13:17-18) as a standard Israelite military formation for surrounding a target. By positioning ambushes on multiple approach routes, Abimelech ensured that Gaal could not escape or receive reinforcements from outside the city. The military competence of a tyrant — Abimelech shows genuine tactical skill — does not legitimize his cause but explains how he maintained power for three years.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Gaal comes out and stands at the city gate as Abimelech rises from the ambush. The city gate was the command center of ancient city defense — the gate complex included guard towers, storage rooms, and the only viable exit for a sortieing force. Gaal's positioning at the gate to observe the surrounding terrain suggests military training; what he sees, and his initial attempt to dismiss it as shadows (v36), is the narrative's way of showing his defeat already beginning through his own misreading of the situation. Zebul's taunt in v38 — 'where is your mouth now?' — is the interpretive climax of Gaal's empty boast.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Gaal's first sighting of Abimelech's troops is dismissed — 'You see the shadow of the mountains as if they were men.' Zebul's initial deception, suggesting the troops are mountain shadows, buys Abimelech time to complete his approach. The motif of misreading terrain as cover for an enemy approach recurs in ancient military narratives; the Trojan Horse and similar stratagems work by exploiting the defender's wish to believe the benign interpretation. Gaal's subsequent recantation (v37) shows he knew the truth but let himself be reassured too quickly — a tactical failure that Zebul cynically enabled.</p>",
    "37": "<p>When the second sighting is unmistakable — troops approaching from the direction of the Diviners' Oak — Gaal can no longer deny the ambush. The 'Diviners' Oak' (<em>ʾēlôn mĕʿônĕnîm</em>) is a sacred tree associated with divination and likely near the Shechem sanctuary complex. Its use as a landmark in the battle narrative suggests it was a well-known topographic feature visible from the city gate. The presence of a divination site in the battle geography underscores the religious character of the entire Shechem narrative — Abimelech is attacking not just a city but the cultic center of Baal-Berith.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'Where is your mouth now, you who said, Who is Abimelech, that we should serve him?' Zebul's taunt at the moment of battle is one of the more satisfying reversals in Judges — the loyalist who had endured Gaal's boast now witnesses its exposure. The rhetorical question 'Is this not the people you despised?' forces Gaal to engage an enemy he had dismissed. The moment when empty political speech meets military reality is a recurring biblical theme: Pharaoh's rhetorical 'Who is YHWH?' (Exod 5:2) is answered by ten plagues; Sennacherib's boasts (2 Kings 18) are answered by an angel and a retreat.</p>",
    "39": "<p>'So Gaal went out at the head of the leaders of Shechem and fought with Abimelech.' Gaal has no choice — he leads the sortie that his boasting had made inevitable. The battle is swift: Abimelech pursues him, many fall, Gaal flees back to the gate. The speed of Gaal's defeat (two verses, 39-40) contrasts with the elaborate political buildup of the preceding seven verses. The gap between his boasting and his performance is the narrative's judgment on opportunistic political demagogues who exploit others' grievances without the character to sustain the fight they provoke.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Abimelech pursues Gaal and many fall wounded 'as far as the entrance of the gate.' The specific detail 'as far as the gate' indicates that Gaal's rout was complete — he barely made it back inside the city before Abimelech could enter with him. The city gate served as the final fallback position; holding the gate meant the city could be defended; losing it meant the city was taken. Gaal's survivors only escaped total destruction by the gate's closing — a military cliff-hanger that sets up Zebul's expulsion of Gaal in the aftermath.</p>",
    "41": "<p>'And Abimelech lived at Arumah, and Zebul drove out Gaal and his relatives, so that they could not dwell at Shechem.' With Gaal expelled, Abimelech consolidates his control: the rebel is purged while Abimelech maintains his base at Arumah (location uncertain, possibly in the Ephraim highlands). The political aftermath — purge the rebel, restore the city's nominal loyalty, then strike decisively — follows standard ancient Near Eastern post-rebellion procedure. That Abimelech allows Zebul to handle the expulsion rather than doing it himself suggests a deliberate delegation of the politically messy task of purging former allies.</p>",
    "42": "<p>'On the following day, the people went out into the field, and Abimelech was told.' The Shechemites emerging into their fields the day after Gaal's expulsion suggests they expected the immediate crisis to be over — Gaal was gone, the conflict resolved. Instead, Abimelech uses their unguarded movement outside the city walls to execute a final, decisive strike. The intelligence network again: someone tells Abimelech immediately. The Shechemites' failure to anticipate continued threat reflects their political naivety; having expelled the rebel, they expected to return to normal relations with their king.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Abimelech divides into three companies again — the tactical flexibility of the multi-company formation allows him to ambush the people in the fields while simultaneously taking a position to cut off the city gate. The precision of the operation (ambush in the fields + gate seizure) demonstrates coordinated planning, not reactive violence. The people in the fields cannot retreat to the city; the people in the city cannot sortie to help them. The tactical pincer eliminates the rebel city with the same methodical completeness that characterizes the worst atrocities of ancient warfare.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The companies rush in to hold the city gate while the other companies strike down the people in the fields. The seizure of the gate — the city's only defended exit/entrance — was the decisive action that made the subsequent slaughter possible. In ancient siege warfare, controlling the gate determined who could escape and who could receive supplies. By taking the gate first, Abimelech turned Shechem from a defensible city into a trap: those inside were sealed in; those outside were exposed. The political coup that had begun with 70 murders on a stone ends with comprehensive urban massacre.</p>",
    "45": "<p>Abimelech fought against the city all day, captured it, killed its people, and 'razed the city and sowed it with salt.' The salting of a captured city is attested in other ANE sources (the Hittite oath formulas curse violators with salt-sowing) as a symbolic act of permanent desolation — the land is made ritually infertile, fit only for cursed occupation. Archaeological evidence from Stratum XI at Tell Balata (ancient Shechem) shows a destruction level consistent with the Late Bronze/Early Iron Age that corresponds to this narrative. The salt-sowing enacts Jotham's curse: the bramble fire devoured the cedar.</p>",
    "46": "<p>'When all the leaders of the Tower of Shechem heard of it, they entered the stronghold of the house of El-Berith.' The Tower of Shechem was apparently a distinct fortification from the main city — possibly the upper citadel or the Beth-millo of v6. The leaders flee to the temple stronghold of El-Berith (God of the Covenant) — using the sacred precinct as a refuge, a common ancient practice since temples were considered inviolable sanctuary. Excavations at Shechem have uncovered a large migdal (tower-temple) from the Middle Bronze Age that continued in use into the Iron Age — likely the El-Berith/Baal-Berith temple complex of Judges 9.</p>",
    "47": "<p>'Abimelech was told that all the leaders of the Tower of Shechem were gathered together.' Abimelech's informant network continues to function even during the battle — he receives intelligence about the temple refuge and responds immediately. The speed of his response (he goes to Mount Zalmon immediately, v48) suggests a prepared contingency plan for exactly this scenario: burning the temple if its occupants used it as a last refuge. This anticipation of the sanctuary-refuge tactic and pre-planning the response reveals the methodical character of Abimelech's violence — nothing is improvised.</p>",
    "48": "<p>'Abimelech went up to Mount Zalmon, he and all the people who were with him. And Abimelech took an axe in his hand and cut down a bundle of brushwood and took it up and laid it on his shoulder.' Mount Zalmon ('dark/shady mountain') is near Shechem; its forested slopes provided the brushwood fuel for the burning. The detail of Abimelech personally cutting brushwood and carrying it on his shoulder is a leadership-by-example detail that reveals a different dimension of his character: whatever his tyranny, he leads from the front and performs the same physical labor he demands of his troops.</p>",
    "49": "<p>'So every one of the people cut down his bundle and following Abimelech put it against the stronghold, and they set the stronghold on fire over them, so that all the people of the Tower of Shechem also died, about 1,000 men and women.' The burning of the temple with its occupants is the largest single death toll in Judges. The Baal-Berith temple that had funded Abimelech's coup becomes the crematorium of his enemies — the circular irony is theologically pointed: the money that purchased Abimelech's kingship (v4) came from this temple; the temple's destruction completes the cycle of covenant-curse retribution that Jotham had invoked.</p>",
    "50": "<p>Abimelech's final campaign takes him to Thebez — 'he went to Thebez and encamped against Thebez and captured it.' Thebez (likely Tubas, northeast of Shechem) was another city whose inhabitants presumably supported Shechem's rebellion against Abimelech. The swift capture and siege pattern is identical to the Shechem operation — Abimelech's military momentum continues seamlessly from one city to the next. The narrative pacing accelerates: Shechem's destruction took all day (v45); Thebez is captured in one sentence.</p>",
    "51": "<p>'But there was a strong tower within the city, and all the men and women and all the leaders of the city fled to it and shut themselves in, and they went up to the roof of the tower.' The strong tower (migdal) within the city was the final defensive refuge — the same tactic as the Shechem leadership's flight to the El-Berith stronghold. Ancient city architecture typically included a central tower that could serve as a last redoubt; its roof elevation gave defenders a position from which to drop projectiles on attackers. The Thebez leadership's flight to the tower roof anticipates what comes next.</p>",
    "52": "<p>'And Abimelech came to the tower and fought against it and drew near to the door of the tower to burn it with fire.' Abimelech repeats exactly the Shechem tactic — approach the tower door to burn it — without apparent awareness that the Shechem operation has transferred to a new and more dangerous context. At Shechem, the occupants of the burning temple were inside and could not throw projectiles; at Thebez, the defenders are on the roof above the door. Abimelech's tactical repetition without situational adjustment is the military failure that ends his reign.</p>",
    "54": "<p>'Then he called quickly to the young man his armor-bearer and said to him, Draw your sword and thrust me through, lest they say about me, A woman killed him.' Abimelech's final concern — dying by a woman's hand — reflects the profound shame attached to such a death in ancient warrior culture. Being killed by a woman was the ultimate military humiliation in ANE warfare (cf. Sisera's death in Judg 4-5). His request to his armor-bearer to run him through is the same tactic Saul uses at Gilboa (1 Sam 31:4-5): preempting a shameful death by a morally preferred one at a trusted companion's hand. Deborah's prophecy (4:9) is thus fulfilled in a way that haunts Israelite military history.</p>",
    "55": "<p>'And when the men of Israel saw that Abimelech was dead, every man departed to his home.' The immediate dispersal of Abimelech's army upon his death reveals the nature of his power: it was entirely personal, held together by his presence and force of will. Unlike YHWH-appointed judges whose deliverance created a covenant community that sustained itself beyond the judge's life, Abimelech's rule dissolved with his person. His army was a mercenary coalition (funded from the Baal-Berith treasury, v4), not a covenant people; when the paymaster died, the coalition disbanded.</p>",
    "56": "<p>'Thus God returned the evil of Abimelech, which he did to his father in killing his seventy brothers.' The theological epilogue (vv56-57) is the Deuteronomistic narrator's explicit statement of divine retribution. The term <em>hēšîb</em> (returned, repaid) is the technical legal term for covenant enforcement — YHWH's action is not vengeance but juridical repayment. The crime (seventy brothers killed) and the retribution (Abimelech killed and his co-conspirators destroyed) are proportionate and structurally linked: the violence done on the stone at Ophrah is answered by the stone dropped from a tower at Thebez.</p>",
    "57": "<p>'And God also made all the evil of the men of Shechem return on their heads, and upon them came the curse of Jotham the son of Jerubbaal.' The double epilogue — God repaid Abimelech AND God repaid Shechem — corresponds to the double invocation of Jotham's curse (v20: fire from Abimelech consuming Shechem, AND fire from Shechem consuming Abimelech). The Deuteronomistic narrator identifies Jotham's curse as the instrument of divine justice: prophetic speech does not merely predict but enacts covenant consequences. The fable's structural logic — the bramble destroys what it pretends to protect — is executed with historical precision.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Tola son of Puah, son of Dodo, from the tribe of Issachar — one of the 'minor judges' about whom minimal narrative information is preserved. The minor judges (Tola, Jair, Ibzan, Elon, Abdon; cf. 12:8-15) appear in lists that record their judgeships, tribal origin, and deaths without deliverance narratives. Scholars debate whether these were local civic leaders/arbiters (legal judges) or whether they also delivered Israel from enemies, with the tradition having lost their narratives. Tola lived at Shamir in the hill country of Ephraim — the same general territory as Deborah (4:5) and the house of Joseph.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Tola judged Israel twenty-three years and died and was buried in Shamir. The twenty-three year tenure is one of the longer minor-judge periods. The minor judges' records preserve the names of their burial sites — Shamir, Kamon (v5) — suggesting these details were preserved in local tradition or administrative records. The combination of tribal affiliation, parentage, location, tenure length, and burial site suggests a formal archival tradition behind the minor-judge lists, possibly associated with the sanctuary at Shiloh or local tribal administrative records.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jair the Gileadite arose after Tola and judged Israel twenty-two years. The double qualification 'the Gileadite' identifies him with the Transjordanian tribal territory east of the Jordan — Gilead was a major region including parts of Gad and Manasseh east of the Jordan. The Transjordanian judges (Jair; later Jephthah, also from Gilead) reflect the full geographic scope of the judge tradition, which was not limited to the west-bank tribes. Jair's name is also that of an earlier Manassite clan-leader (Num 32:41; Deut 3:14) who had settled east-Manasseh territory — the judge may be associated with this clan tradition.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jair had thirty sons who rode on thirty donkeys and had thirty cities — 'Havvoth-jair' ('tent-villages of Jair') — in the land of Gilead. The thirty-son, thirty-donkey, thirty-city correlation is a standard chieftain's formula indicating both political influence (many sons = multiple heirs and allies) and economic control (each city = a revenue center). Donkeys as mounts for notables recurs throughout Judges (the white donkeys of the Song of Deborah, 5:10) and reflects the pre-horse transportation of the Iron Age I period. The Havvoth-jair are mentioned in Num 32:41 and Deut 3:14, suggesting long-standing clan tenure in this territory.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jair died and was buried in Kamon. Kamon's location is disputed — Jerome identified it with a site in the Decapolis region; modern candidates include Tell el-Qaimun or a site in northern Gilead. The terse burial notice closes the Jair entry with the same archival finality as the other minor-judge records. What is notable about Jair's entry as a whole is what it lacks: no enemy oppression, no cry to YHWH, no Spirit-empowerment, no deliverance narrative — only the quiet civic tenure of a leader whose era was apparently one of peace and stability, perhaps because the covenant remained intact during his administration.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'And the anger of YHWH was kindled against Israel, and he sold them into the hand of the Philistines and into the hand of the Ammonites.' The double oppression — Philistines (coastal plain, west) and Ammonites (Transjordan, east) — is unique in Judges and creates a geographically comprehensive squeeze on Israel from both sides of the Jordan. This double threat sets the stage for two separate deliverers: Jephthah against Ammon (ch11-12) and eventually Samson against the Philistines (ch13-16). The narrative structure of Judges 10-16 is thus a double-strand that the editor has interleaved: the Ammonite crisis is resolved first, the Philistine crisis extends through the Samson cycle.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'They crushed and oppressed the people of Israel that year. For eighteen years they oppressed all the people of Israel who were beyond the Jordan in the land of the Amorites, which is in Gilead.' The eighteen-year oppression — concentrated in the Transjordanian Gilead region — explains why a Gileadite leader (Jephthah) will emerge as the deliverer. The Ammonites claiming Gilead as their historical territory (11:13) is the political claim that underlies the military pressure; the oppression is the enforcement arm of a territorial dispute that will require legal-diplomatic as well as military resolution. Jephthah's double role as negotiator and warrior corresponds to this dual (diplomatic + military) character of the crisis.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The Ammonites also crossed the Jordan to fight against Judah and against Benjamin and against the house of Ephraim, so that Israel was severely distressed.' The Ammonite crossing of the Jordan from Transjordan into the west-bank tribal territories elevated the crisis from a Transjordanian border dispute to an existential threat to the entire tribal confederation. The specific naming of Judah, Benjamin, and Ephraim — the southern, central, and central-northern tribes — suggests a broad Ammonite offensive rather than a targeted raid. The phrase 'severely distressed' (<em>wayyēṣar lĕyiśrāʾēl mĕʾōd</em>) is the standard pre-deliverance vocabulary, signaling the imminent cry and divine response.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'And the people of Israel cried out to YHWH, saying, We have sinned against you, because we have forsaken our God and have served the Baals.' The covenant confession includes specific acknowledgment: 'we have forsaken our God and served the Baals.' The specificity of the confession — naming the precise violation (Baal worship) rather than offering a generic apology — is notable. This is one of the more substantive confessions in Judges, combined with the subsequent YHWH-response in v11-14 that demands more than verbal confession. The exchange in vv10-16 is theologically the most developed divine-Israel dialogue in the book.</p>",
    "12": "<p>YHWH's expanded recital of past deliverances — Egypt, Amorites, Ammon, Philistines, Sidon, Amalek, Maon — is the most comprehensive historical review in Judges, demonstrating through accumulation that Israel has been rescued from all these same or similar threats before. The inclusion of Maon (possibly the Maonites, cf. 2 Chr 26:7) among the deliverances is difficult; some manuscripts read 'Midian.' The rhetorical point is a list of precedents: YHWH has proven his willingness to rescue Israel repeatedly, which makes the continued apostasy all the more inexcusable — they sin against a demonstrated track record of covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Yet you have forsaken me and served other gods; therefore I will save you no more.' YHWH's declaration of withdrawal is unprecedented in Judges — no previous judge cycle features YHWH threatening to end the deliverer pattern entirely. The threat 'I will save you no more' is a conditional covenant curse (cf. Deut 28:25: 'YHWH will cause you to be defeated before your enemies') taken to its logical extreme. The purpose of this unprecedented threat in the narrative is to force a more fundamental response from Israel than the rote cry-repent-receive pattern that the earlier cycles had established. YHWH refuses to be a predictable rescue machine.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'And the people of Israel said to YHWH, We have sinned; do to us whatever seems good to you. Only please deliver us this day.' The second confession (after v10) adds the submission formula: 'do to us whatever seems good to you' — an unconditional surrender to YHWH's judgment, followed by the plea for deliverance. The combination of total submission and continued petition is the proper covenant posture that YHWH's v13-14 address demanded. This confession moves from formula (v10) to genuine surrender — the difference between apologizing for consequences and accepting the covenant lord's authority over the situation entirely. It is met by the divine relenting of v16.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Then the Ammonites were called to arms, and they encamped in Gilead. And the people of Israel came together, and they encamped at Mizpah.' The military mobilization on both sides — Ammon in Gilead, Israel at Mizpah — sets up the leadership crisis of v18. Mizpah in Gilead (different from the west-bank Mizpah of Judges 20-21 and Samuel) was an important Transjordanian sanctuary; its name means 'watchtower.' The assembly at a sacred site before battle is standard Israelite holy-war procedure; the crisis is that there is no designated military leader, which is why the question of v18 becomes urgent.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'And the people, the leaders of Gilead, said one to another, Who is the man who will begin to fight against the Ammonites? He shall be head over all the inhabitants of Gilead.' The Gileadite leaders' question — and their offer of permanent leadership to whoever answers it — is the setup for Jephthah's call in ch11. The offer of <em>rōʾš</em> (head/chief) status creates a crisis of legitimacy similar to the one Abimelech exploited in ch9: when leadership is offered to whoever will fight, rather than given by YHWH to whom he chooses, the result is predictably problematic. Jephthah's negotiation of his leadership terms (11:9-11) shows he recognized the offer's structural parallels to Abimelech's coup and insisted on covenant-proper authorization.</p>"
  }
}

